{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013nXX1VkZEzswPakvtvAjR4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The ConfigMap already has:\n1. `allow-snippet-annotations: \"true\"` - allows using server-snippet/configuration-snippet\n2. `http-snippet: limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=api_zone:10m rate=20r/m;` - a global rate limit zone defined at http level\n3. `limit-req-status-code: \"429\"` - returns 429 for rate-limited requests\n\nSo there's already a `limit_req_zone` defined at the http level named `api_zone` with rate 20r/m (0.33 req/s per replica). \n\nI can apply this zone to the `/api` path by adding a `configuration-snippet` annotation to the `rate-api` ingress that references the `api_zone`. With 3 replicas, this gives us roughly 1 request per second globally, which matches what we need.\n\nLet me trace through how the rate limiting will actually behave during testing. At 2 requests per second globally (about 0.67 per replica), the first request passes through with no excess, then subsequent requests accumulate excess tokens based on the 0.33 req/s rate and the burst allowance of 1.\n\nBy the fourth request to a single replica around 4.5 seconds, the excess accumulates to 1.5, which exceeds the burst limit and gets rejected. So across all three replicas handling the test traffic, I'd expect most requests to pass but eventually hit rejections as the excess builds up. Since each replica maintains its own independent rate limit zone based on the client IP, this per-replica analysis is the right way to think about it.\n\nNow I'm considering what happens with burst=0 instead. Nginx doesn't actually allow burst=0 in the traditional sense—the minimum is effectively 0 when you omit the burst parameter entirely, which means any request exceeding the rate gets immediately rejected. With a rate of 20 requests per minute (about one request every 3 seconds), the second request at 1.5 seconds would already exceed the limit and get rejected outright.\n\nLooking at the pattern across multiple replicas, I'm seeing an alternating pass-reject sequence emerge for each replica, and now I need to carefully map which global request number lands on which replica to understand the overall behavior. So out of 10 requests, 6 pass and 4 get rejected, giving an effective rate of 1.2 requests per second—that's the rate limiting in action. For nginx, I need to use `nodelay` to get immediate rejection instead of queuing, since the default behavior without it would delay excess requests rather than reject them outright. So without burst specified, the default is 0, meaning any request arriving too quickly gets rejected with 429 immediately—there's no delay queue to absorb excess requests. This confirms the alternating pass/reject pattern I calculated earlier, resulting in about 6 successful requests per minute. So with this setup, roughly half the requests get through, giving an effective global rate of about 1.2 requests per second across all three replicas. My final plan is to add the rate limiting configuration snippet to the `rate-api` ingress that references the pre-configured `api_zone` from the ConfigMap, which already has the right settings for 20 requests per minute with burst disabled and 429 status codes. The `/health` endpoint stays unrestricted as intended.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10507,"cache_read_input_tokens":31809,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10507},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8440b52f-af86-4554-9ef5-a5048d047c58","uuid":"125f1fd2-6ecb-4fe3-92fb-8de8d82971a8","request_id":"req_011CcMQKzD7pYi3dfQ4Q4iAy"}
